The perfect is largely used in Greek for the maintenance of the result,
							and the translation into English is often present: ke/klhmai, my name is;
							me/mnhmai, I have recalled, I
								remember;
							ke/kthmai, I have got, I
								own;
							ei)/qismai, I have made it my
								rule, I am accustomed.

ei) ga\r prolei/yeis m(e) . . ., oi)xo/mesqa (oi)xo/mesqa is
							a practical perfect), EUR. Or. 304-5;
								If thou shalt abandon me, I am gone (lost).

So with the moods and verbals: e)a\n
								nosh/sh|, if he falls sick;
							mh\ nosh/saimi, may I not fall
